  "justification": "The answer includes a specific statistic and citation: 'According to the American Academy of Pediatrics, students who eat a complete lunch demonstrate improved concentration and academic performance in the hours that follow.' and 'The United States alone discards approximately 50 billion plastic water bottles per year, and only about 23 percent of those are recycled, according to the Container Recycling Institute.' These claims are presented as factual with specific numbers and named organizations but lack verifiable grounding or sources. Therefore, they qualify as hallucinations under the rubric.",
  "corrected_answer": "{\n  \"hallucinations_found\": false,\n  \"types\": [],\n  \"justification\": \"No prior AI-generated answer was provided to evaluate for hallucinations. The request is to generate a new lesson plan, so there is nothing to fact-check against.\",\n  \"corrected_answer\": \"LESSON PLAN: Writing Arguments with Clear Reasons and Evidence\\nGrade Level: 7th Grade | Subject: ELA | Duration: 55 Minutes\\nStandard: CCSS.ELA-Literacy.W.7.1\\n\\n---\\n\\nOBJECTIVE:\\nStudents will be able to identify the components of a strong argument (claim, reasons, evidence, counterclaim, rebuttal), evaluate a sample argument, and begin drafting their own argumentative paragraph using logical organization.\\n\\n---\\n\\nMATERIALS NEEDED:\\n- Whiteboard or projector\\n- Printed or projected sample argument passage (provided below)\\n- Argument Graphic Organizer handout (one per student)\\n- Writing paper or notebooks\\n- Colored pens or highlighters (3 colors per student or pair)\\n- Optional: mini sticky notes\\n\\n---\\n\\nVOCABULARY TO PRE-TEACH (displayed on board throughout lesson):\\n- Claim: The main argument or position you are taking\\n- Reason: Why your claim is true\\n- Evidence: Facts, data, quotes, or examples that support your reason\\n- Counterclaim: An opposing viewpoint someone else might hold\\n- Rebuttal: Your response that addresses and refutes the counterclaim\\n\\n---\\n\\nSEGMENT 1 \u2014 HOOK AND ACTIVATION (0:00\u20130:08 | 8 minutes)\\n\\nActivity: 'Take a Stand'\\n- Clear desks to the sides or simply ask students to stand.\\n- Read a series of debatable statements aloud. Students physically move to one side of the room for AGREE, the other for DISAGREE, or stand in the middle for UNSURE.\\n  * Statement 1: 'Middle schoolers should have homework every night.'\\n  * Statement 2: 'School should start later in the morning.'\\n  * Statement 3: 'Students should be allowed to use their phones during lunch.'\\n- After each statement, ask 1\u20132 students from each side: 'WHY do you think that?'\\n- After returning to seats, ask: 'What did you just do when you explained your position?' Guide students to the idea that they were making ARGUMENTS.\\n- Teacher says: 'Today we are going to learn how to take that thinking and turn it into powerful WRITTEN arguments that are organized, logical, and convincing.'\\n\\n---\\n\\nSEGMENT 2 \u2014 DIRECT INSTRUCTION: THE ARGUMENT FRAMEWORK (0:08\u20130:20 | 12 minutes)\\n\\nMini-Lesson: Building Blocks of an Argument\\n- Write the following structure on the board and explain each part with a quick example:\\n\\n  CLAIM \u2192 REASON \u2192 EVIDENCE \u2192 COUNTERCLAIM \u2192 REBUTTAL\\n\\n- Use a simple, relatable example to model each component:\\n\\n  Topic: Should students have a longer lunch period?\\n\\n  CLAIM: 'Middle school students should be given at least 35 minutes for lunch.'\\n  REASON: 'Students need adequate time to eat a full meal and briefly socialize in order to focus better in afternoon classes.'\\n  EVIDENCE: 'Research shows that students who eat a complete lunch demonstrate improved concentration and academic performance in the hours that follow.'\\n  COUNTERCLAIM: 'Some may argue that a longer lunch period wastes valuable instructional time that could be used for learning.'\\n  REBUTTAL: 'However, students who are hungry or rushed are less productive in class, meaning a longer lunch actually protects instructional time rather than reducing it.'\\n\\n- After modeling, ask students: 'What makes this argument stronger than just saying I think lunch should be longer because I like it?'\\n- Discuss: specificity, logic, acknowledging the other side, using real evidence.\\n- Introduce the acronym CREER (Claim, Reason, Evidence, [counter]claim, Rebuttal) written on the board as a memory tool.\\n\\n---\\n\\nSEGMENT 3 \u2014 GUIDED PRACTICE: ANALYZE A SAMPLE ARGUMENT (0:20\u20130:33 | 13 minutes)\\n\\nActivity: Color-Code the Argument\\n- Distribute the sample argument passage below (printed or projected).\\n- Assign colors: Color 1 = Claim, Color 2 = Evidence/Reasons, Color 3 = Counterclaim and Rebuttal\\n- Students work in PAIRS to read and highlight or underline each component.\\n\\nSAMPLE ARGUMENT PASSAGE (to print or project):\\n---\\n'Schools should ban single-use plastic water bottles from their campuses. The most important reason is the significant environmental damage caused by plastic waste. Many plastic bottles end up in landfills or natural waterways, harming wildlife and polluting ecosystems for hundreds of years. Some people argue that banning plastic bottles infringes on personal choice and that students may not stay properly hydrated without convenient bottle access. However, this concern is easily addressed by ensuring that water refill stations are installed throughout the school, giving students a sustainable and equally convenient alternative. Protecting the environment is a responsibility that schools can and should model for future generations.'\\n---\\n\\n- After 5 minutes of partner work, bring the class together.\\n- Call on student pairs to share: 'What did you identify as the claim? What was tricky?'\\n- Discuss as a class, clarifying any confusion about the difference between a reason and evidence, or between a counterclaim and a rebuttal.\\n- Ask a higher-order question: 'Is this argument convincing? What would make it EVEN stronger?'\\n\\n---\\n\\nSEGMENT 4 \u2014 INDEPENDENT PRACTICE: PLAN YOUR OWN ARGUMENT (0:33\u20130:48 | 15 minutes)\\n\\nActivity: Argument Graphic Organizer\\n- Distribute the Argument Graphic Organizer (described below).\\n- Students choose ONE of the following provided prompts OR may use the school-start-time topic from the warm-up:\\n  * Prompt A: Should students be required to wear school uniforms?\\n  * Prompt B: Should junk food be banned from school vending machines?\\n  * Prompt C: Should students be graded on effort rather than only on test scores?\\n\\n- Students complete the graphic organizer independently:\\n\\n  ARGUMENT GRAPHIC ORGANIZER:\\n  [ My Topic: _________________________________ ]\\n  [ My CLAIM (What is your position?): _________ ]\\n  [ REASON 1 (Why is your claim true?): ________ ]\\n  [ EVIDENCE for Reason 1 (fact, statistic, example, or expert opinion): ________ ]\\n  [ REASON 2 (optional): ________ ]\\n  [ EVIDENCE for Reason 2: ________ ]\\n  [ COUNTERCLAIM (What might someone who disagrees say?): ________ ]\\n  [ REBUTTAL (How do you respond to that opposing view?): ________ ]\\n\\n- Teacher circulates the room, conferring briefly with students:\\n  * Check that claims are specific positions, not just topics.\\n  * Prompt students whose evidence is vague: 'Can you add a number, a name, or a real example to make this stronger?'\\n  * Help students who struggle to write a counterclaim by asking: 'If someone in class disagreed with you, what might they say?'\\n\\n- With 3 minutes remaining, students should begin turning their organizer into a first-draft argumentative paragraph in their notebooks, using their graphic organizer as a guide.\\n\\n---\\n\\nSEGMENT 5 \u2014 SHARE AND REFLECT (0:48\u20130:55 | 7 minutes)\\n\\nActivity: Peer Share and Class Debrief\\n- Ask 2\u20133 volunteers (or use cold-calling with an equity stick/random name selector) to read their CLAIM and COUNTERCLAIM aloud.\\n- After each student shares, ask the class: 'Does this claim take a clear position? Is the counterclaim a real opposing view that someone might actually hold?'\\n- Brief class discussion: 'What was hardest about planning your argument today?'\\n  Common expected responses: finding real evidence, thinking of the other side, making a specific claim.\\n- Teacher affirms the challenge: 'Good argument writers don't just say what they believe \u2014 they PROVE it and they show they've thought about it from all angles. That is exactly what you practiced today.'\\n\\nEXIT TICKET (last 3 minutes of this segment):\\n- On a sticky note or half-sheet of paper, students answer:\\n  1. In ONE sentence, write your CLAIM for your chosen topic.\\n  2. Name ONE piece of evidence you plan to use.\\n  3. What is one question you still have about writing arguments?\\n- Collect exit tickets as students leave. Use responses to inform the next day's instruction and identify students who need additional support.\\n\\n---\\n\\nDIFFERENTIATION:\\n\\nFor Students Needing Support:\\n- Provide a sentence starter bank (e.g., 'I believe that...', 'One reason is...', 'For example...', 'Some people argue that...', 'However...')\\n- Pre-fill part of the graphic organizer with the topic and a suggested claim for them to refine.\\n- Pair with a stronger writing partner during guided practice.\\n\\nFor Advanced Students:\\n- Challenge them to include TWO counterclaims with individual rebuttals.\\n- Ask them to evaluate the credibility of their evidence source: 'How do you know this evidence is reliable?'\\n- Encourage them to consider the TONE of their argument and whether word choice strengthens their position.\\n\\nFor English Language Learners:\\n- Provide the vocabulary terms with visual icons or translations.\\n- Allow the use of a bilingual dictionary during independent practice.\\n- Offer the graphic organizer with sentence frames built into each box.\\n\\n---\\n\\nASSESSMENT:\\n- Formative: Observation during 'Take a Stand,' color-coding accuracy during guided practice, and exit ticket responses.\\n- The completed graphic organizer and draft paragraph serve as a pre-assessment of student readiness before the full argumentative writing assignment.\\n- The exit ticket question 3 drives differentiated re-teaching in the next lesson.\\n\\n---\\n\\nEXTENSION / HOMEWORK (optional):\\n- Students finish their draft argumentative paragraph at home, using their completed graphic organizer.\\n- Students find ONE real piece of evidence (a statistic, quote, or example from a credible source) to strengthen their argument and bring it to the next class.\\n\\n---\\n\\nSTANDARDS ALIGNMENT:\\n- CCSS.ELA-Literacy.W.7.1a \u2014 Introduce a claim and organize reasons and evidence clearly\\n- CCSS.ELA-Literacy.W.7.1b \u2014 Support claim(s) with logical reasoning and relevant evidence\\n- CCSS.ELA-Literacy.W.7.1c \u2014 Use words, phrases, and clauses to create cohesion and clarify relationships\\n- CCSS.ELA-Literacy.W.7.1e \u2014 Provide a concluding statement related to the argument\\n- CCSS.ELA-Literacy.SL.7.1 \u2014 Engage in collaborative discussions (Take a Stand activity, peer share)\"\n}"
